def: Axioms are propositions that we assume are true ( greek for "assume worthy")

Ex: if a = b and b = c then a = c ( no proof, however its an axiom)

Axioms can be contradictory in certain contexts

Euclidean geometry: Given a line L and a point P not on L, there is exactly one line through P parallel to L
Spherical geometry: Given a line L and a point P not on L, there is NO line on through P parallel to L
Hyperbolic geometry:                                     , there are infinitely many lines through P parallel to L

Two guiding principles to axioms:

Axioms should be
1. consistent
2. complete

def: a set of axioms is consistent if no proposition can be proved to be both true and false
def: a set of axioms is complete if it can be used to prove every proposition is either true or false

